Net Migration¶

In [ ]:
migration_test = migration[['Year', 'Migration Percentage of Population']]
migration_test = migration_test.set_index('Year')
migration_test.plot()
Out[ ]:
<Axes: xlabel='Year'>

Looking at the graph there might be some seasonality in the way of the economic cycles, where crises could have an affect on the migration numbers. However, since the data is on a yearly interval, it is not possible to substantiate this with a statistical test.

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test¶

In [ ]:
X = migration_test.values
result = adfuller(X)
print('ADF Statistic: %f' % result[0])
print('p-value: %f' % result[1])

# p-value is less than 0.05, so the data is stationary (constant variance over time)

ADF Statistic: -3.149299
p-value: 0.023114

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test¶

In [ ]:
X = emigration_test.values
result = adfuller(X)
print('ADF Statistic: %f' % result[0])
print('p-value: %f' % result[1])

# p-value is higher than 0.1, so the data is non-stationary (non-constant variance over time) 
# in other words, it has some time-dependent structure and does not have constant variance over time

ADF Statistic: -1.791410
p-value: 0.384735

KPSS Test¶

In [ ]:
#perform KPSS test
sm.tsa.stattools.kpss(emigration_test.values, regression='ct')

# The p-value is significant on a 10% level, but not on a 5% level,
# which means that time series is not highly non-stationary according to the KPSS test 
# but as seen from the ADF test and this KPSS test, the data is not stationary

Make emigration data stationary through differencing (order = 3)¶

In [ ]:
diff = emigration_test.diff()
diff = diff.diff()
diff = diff.diff()
pyplot.plot(diff)
pyplot.show()
In [ ]:
diff = diff.dropna()
In [ ]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
X = diff.values
result = adfuller(X)
print('ADF Statistic: %f' % result[0])
print('p-value: %f' % result[1])

# p-value is higher than 0.1, so the data is non-stationary (non-constant variance over time) 
# in other words, it has some time-dependent structure and does not have constant variance over time

p-value: 0.012569

Make Percentages for Variables where could be needed¶

In [ ]:
for index, row in Net_Migration.iterrows():
    Year = row['Year']

    # Get M1 values 
    M1_current_year = row['T-1 Net migration 25-44 years']
    M1_previous_year = Net_Migration.loc[index - 1, 'T-1 Net migration 25-44 years'] if index > 0 else None
    M1_percentage_change = (M1_current_year - M1_previous_year) / M1_previous_year * 100 if M1_previous_year else None
 
    # Get M2 values 
    M2_current_year = row['T-1 Emigrants 15-24 years']
    M2_previous_year = Net_Migration.loc[index - 1, 'T-1 Emigrants 15-24 years'] if index > 0 else None
    M2_percentage_change = (M2_current_year - M2_previous_year) / M2_previous_year * 100 if M2_previous_year else None

    # Get M3 values 
    M3_current_year = row['T-1 Emigrants_EU15 to EU27']
    M3_previous_year = Net_Migration.loc[index - 1, 'T-1 Emigrants_EU15 to EU27'] if index > 0 else None
    M3_percentage_change = (M3_current_year - M3_previous_year) / M3_previous_year * 100 if M3_previous_year else None

    # Get M4 values 
    M4_current_year = row['T-1 Enterprises_Ireland_250+']
    M4_previous_year = Net_Migration.loc[index - 1, 'T-1 Enterprises_Ireland_250+'] if index > 0 else None
    M4_percentage_change = (M4_current_year - M4_previous_year) / M4_previous_year * 100 if M4_previous_year else None

    # Get M4 values 
    M5_current_year = row['T-1 General Surplus/Deficit (Million Euros)']
    M5_previous_year = Net_Migration.loc[index - 1, 'T-1 General Surplus/Deficit (Million Euros)'] if index > 0 else None
    M5_percentage_change = (M5_current_year - M5_previous_year) / M5_previous_year * 100 if M5_previous_year else None

    # Store to dataframe
    Net_Migration.loc[index, 'T-1 Net migration 25-44 years Percentage Change'] = M1_percentage_change
    Net_Migration.loc[index, 'T-1 Emigrants 15-24 years Percentage Change'] = M2_percentage_change
    Net_Migration.loc[index, 'T-1 Emigrants_EU15 to EU27 Percentage Change'] = M3_percentage_change
    Net_Migration.loc[index, 'T-1 Enterprises_Ireland_250+ Percentage Change'] = M4_percentage_change
    Net_Migration.loc[index, 'T-1 General Surplus/Deficit Percentage Change'] = M5_percentage_change

Variable for events with impact net migration¶

Important Years¶

1972: Ireland joins eu (https://ireland.representation.ec.europa.eu/about-us/irelands-eu-membership_en)

1980-1982: early 1980s recession (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Early_1980s_recession)

1987: Black Monday US (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Monday_(1987))

1995: Start Celtic Tiger (boom economy of ireland until 2007: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/celtictiger.asp, https://www.tcd.ie/Economics/staff/dmcleese/Web/mcaleese.pdf)

1997: Asian financial crisis (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Asian_financial_crisis)

2004: EU enlargement (https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/infographics/2004-enlargement-facts-and-figures/)

2007-2008: economic crisis 2008-2010: Irish Banking Crisis (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Post-2008_Irish_banking_crisis)

2016: brexit referendum

2020: brexit and covid

2022: War in Ukraine (https://www.nytimes.com/article/ukraine-russia-war-timeline.html)

Variable for events with impact Emigration¶

Important Years¶

1972: Ireland joins eu (https://ireland.representation.ec.europa.eu/about-us/irelands-eu-membership_en)

1980-1982: early 1980s recession (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Early_1980s_recession)

1987: Black Monday US (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Monday_(1987))

1995: Start Celtic Tiger (boom economy of ireland until 2007: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/celtictiger.asp, https://www.tcd.ie/Economics/staff/dmcleese/Web/mcaleese.pdf)

1997: Asian financial crisis (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Asian_financial_crisis)

2004: EU enlargement (https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/infographics/2004-enlargement-facts-and-figures/)

2007-2008: economic crisis 2008-2010: Irish Banking Crisis (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Post-2008_Irish_banking_crisis)

2016: brexit referendum

2020: brexit and covid

2022: War in Ukraine (https://www.nytimes.com/article/ukraine-russia-war-timeline.html)

Important Years¶

1980-1982: early 1980s recession (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Early_1980s_recession)

1987: Black Monday US (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Monday_(1987))

1995: Start Celtic Tiger (boom economy of ireland until 2007: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/celtictiger.asp, https://www.tcd.ie/Economics/staff/dmcleese/Web/mcaleese.pdf)

1997: Asian financial crisis (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Asian_financial_crisis)

2007-2008: economic crisis 2008-2010: Irish Banking Crisis (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Post-2008_Irish_banking_crisis)

2016: brexit referendum

2020: brexit and covid

2022: War in Ukraine (https://www.nytimes.com/article/ukraine-russia-war-timeline.html)

import numpy as np
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Perform CUSUM test on residuals
res = sm.stats.diagnostic.breaks_cusumolsresid(model_fit.resid)

# Plot the time series data
plt.plot(migration_indexed.index, migration_indexed['residuals'], label='Residuals')

# Plot markers for breakpoints detected by the test
breakpoints = [(migration_indexed.index[i], val) for i, val in res[2]]
for year, val in breakpoints:
    plt.scatter(year, migration_indexed.loc[year, 'residuals'], color='red', label=f'Breakpoint at {year}, val={val}')

# Mark specific years from any_impact_years
any_impact_years = [1972, 1980, 1981, 1982, 1987, 1997, 2004, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2016, 2020, 2022]
for year in any_impact_years:
    if year in migration_indexed.index:
        plt.scatter(year, migration_indexed.loc[year, 'residuals'], color='green', label=f'Year with Impact: {year}')

# Set plot labels and legend
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Time Series with CUSUM Breakpoints and Impact Years')
plt.legend()

# Show plot
plt.show()
